  "prompt": "What's the difference between should, shall and will?",
  "response": "Here's a breakdown of the differences between \"should,\" \"shall,\" and \"will\":\n\n1. Should:\n- Indicates advice or recommendation\n- Suggests what is proper or advisable\n- Expresses a mild obligation\n- Used for giving suggestions\nExample: \"You should eat more vegetables.\"\n\n2. Shall:\n- Formal way of expressing future action\n- Used in legal or official documents\n- Indicates a strong intention or promise\n- Often used in first-person (I/we) to express determination\nExample: \"We shall overcome.\"\n\n3. Will:\n- Most common way to express future actions\n- Indicates prediction or expectation\n- Shows willingness or determination\n- Used for all persons (I, you, he/she/it, we, they)\nExample: \"I will call you later.\"\n\nQuick comparison:\n- Should = Advice\n- Shall = Formal intention\n- Will = Simple future action\n\nIn modern English, \"will\" is used more frequently, and \"shall\" is becoming less common in everyday speech.",
